The Indian Buffet Process

Andrew Wong

February 16, 2016

Below is my code for the generative model of the Indian Buffet Process. Following my code is a series of depictions of the IBP results. The purpose of the first plot is to show how difficult it is to see the sparsity of the matrix for a small number of customers, \(N\).

The following plots show what happens as I increase the number of data points, \(N\), and vary the hyperparameter, \(\alpha\). I keep \(N\) fixed for the remaining three plots so we can clearly observe the changes as alpha is varied. Alpha is the dispersion parameter, and we can see that as \(\alpha\) increases, each customer is more likely to try new dishes and evidenced by the maximum value of the x-axis. The number of dishes increases from 39, to 53, to 71 for \(\alpha=\{ 10, 15, 20 \}\) for the same seed. Increasing \(N\) makes the sparsity of the matrices much more clear.

My Code

library(qdap) # qhead() for binary matrix
## begin IBP
seed=1; alpha=10; num_customers = 10
IBP <- function(num_customers,alpha,seed){
  ## initialize variables
  # seed=2
  set.seed(seed)
  dishes_sampled = NULL
  dish_freq = NULL
  customer_record = NULL
  
  ## first customer samples first rpois(alpha) dishes
  dishes_sampled <- rpois(n=1,lambda=alpha)
  
  if(dishes_sampled!=0){
    dishes_sampled <- seq(1,dishes_sampled,by=1); dishes_sampled # dishes sampled
    dish_freq <- as.data.frame(table(dishes_sampled)); dish_freq # dish sampling frequency
    customer_record <- data.frame(customer=c(rep(x=1,times=length(dishes_sampled))),
                                dishes_sampled=dishes_sampled); customer_record ; table(customer_record)
  }
  else{
    stop("try a different seed. first customer is trying 0 dishes")
  }
  ## customer i samples previous dishes
  for(i in 2:num_customers){
    ############################################################
    ## customer i samples previous dishes with probability n/i
    ############################################################
    # i=4;
    set.seed(seed+i);
    boolVector <- runif(n=nrow(dish_freq),min=0,max=1)<dish_freq$Freq/i; boolVector
    dish_freq$dishes_sampled[boolVector] # return dishes sampled
    
    ## create current customer's sampling history
    current_customer <- data.frame(cbind(rep(x=i,times=length(dish_freq$dishes_sampled[boolVector])),
                            dish_freq$dishes_sampled[boolVector])); current_customer
    names(current_customer) <- names(customer_record); current_customer # rename columns for rbind
    
    ## update full record of customer sampling history
    customer_record <- rbind(customer_record, current_customer); customer_record
    
    ## update sampling probability
    dish_freq$Freq <- dish_freq$Freq+as.numeric(boolVector); dish_freq # update dishes_sampled frequency
    
    ############################################################
    ## customer i samples Poisson(alpha/i) number of new dishes
    ############################################################
    new_dishes_sampled = NULL
    # set.seed(i)
    # set.seed(seed)
    new_dishes_sampled <- rpois(n=1,lambda=alpha/i) 
    if(new_dishes_sampled!=0){ # if new_dishes_sampled >0, do the following. else, skip this section
      new_dishes_sampled <- seq(1,new_dishes_sampled,by=1) + length(dishes_sampled); new_dishes_sampled
      dishes_sampled <- c(dishes_sampled,new_dishes_sampled); dishes_sampled
    
      ## create current customer's sampling history
      current_customer <- data.frame(cbind(rep(x=i,times=length(new_dishes_sampled)),
                              new_dishes_sampled)); current_customer
      names(current_customer) <- names(customer_record); current_customer # rename columns for rbind
      
      ## update full record of customer sampling history
      customer_record <- rbind(customer_record, current_customer); customer_record
      
      ## update sampling probability
      current_customer_freq <- data.frame(
        cbind(current_customer$dishes_sampled,
        rep(x=1,times=length(current_customer$dishes_sampled)))); current_customer_freq
      names(current_customer_freq) <- names(dish_freq); current_customer_freq # rename columns for rbind
      current_customer_freq$dishes_sampled <- as.factor(current_customer_freq$dishes_sampled)
      dish_freq <- rbind(dish_freq,current_customer_freq); dish_freq # update dishes_sampled frequency
    }
  }
  ## binary matrix
  mm <- data.frame(matrix(as.logical(table(customer_record)),nrow=i))
  names(mm) <- paste0("dish ",seq(1,ncol(mm),1))
  return(mm)
  # p <- qheat(t(mm), by.column=NULL, high="black", text.color =NA,
    # grid="grey20")
  # return(p)
}
mm1 <- IBP(num_customers = 10,alpha=10,seed=1)
qheat(t(mm1), by.column=NULL, high="black", text.color=NA, grid="grey20")

mm2 <- IBP(num_customers = 20,alpha=10,seed=1)
qheat(t(mm2), by.column=NULL, high="black", text.color=NA, grid="grey20")

mm3 <- IBP(num_customers = 20,alpha=15,seed=1)
qheat(t(mm3), by.column=NULL, high="black", text.color=NA, grid="grey20")

mm4 <- IBP(num_customers = 20,alpha=20,seed=1)
qheat(t(mm4), by.column=NULL, high="black", text.color=NA, grid="grey20")
